caption: I had the chance to visit the Greenhouses of the Luxembourg Gardens during the last Heritage Days on September 22th. Entrance was free and we enjoyed detailed explanations. However, I was not as impressed by the diversity nor the richness of the plants on display. The botanical gardens in other European capitals were much more impressive. In summary, if you are in the area and have time to spare, you may try to visit it, but I would recommend many other places in Paris that are much more worth a visit.

It was one of the best experiences with the European Heritage Days, the greenhouses are amazing. I never saw such a collection of orchids ever. The volunteers and the staff were all extremely helpful and were answering the millions of questions posed by the thousands of curious visitors. I was glad to make it to the place and the experience enriched me and my scientific knowledge as well. Well done and bon courage and Merci beaucoup üôÇ

Taste is usually not an issue, but there are places in the world that most people find admirable. And I think that one of those is the Luxembourg Gardens in Paris (Jardin du Luxembourg).

Rating 6/10 I should say that from how they spoke to me, which is a very rare event I expected to see a lot more, entry was free, we waited in line for about 20 minutes, then we went in, there are some plants outside the greenhouse there are many varieties of sage for example etc.. then we entered the greenhouse which is not very large, it is made up of a corridor with about 8 rooms which you cannot enter but you can only look from the corridor and after that there is a another piece of exterior with many varieties of fruits apple and pear, we visited everything in about 20 minutes, I think we waited longer to enter than to visit

Open especially for heritage days, interesting visit to the greenhouses even if you can only enter at the entrance to the greenhouses. The orchid collection, which dates back 160 years, is particularly impressive!

A magical place in the Luxembourg gardens, the greenhouses particularly hosting a remarkable collection of orchids, the conservatory has more than 10,000, the oldest dating from 1860! Gardeners passionate about the production of green flower plants as well as the conservatory space for apple and pear fruit trees
I loved visiting the greenhouses, with a lot of explanations from the specialists present, even if we couldn't go inside and literally walk among the plants, it was magnificent and very interesting
